Generally speaking, ID is defended on the basis of what philosophers of science call “inference to the best explanation” for the plausibility of design over chance in nature--But ID is NOT about an inference to the best explanation, something trivially shown by asking any ID proponent how ID explains the bacterial flagella, which due to lack of sufficient scientific understanding was claimed to have been "designed'Of course, this somewhat foolish argument sets up Fuller for a scathing response--Grayling:I am, says Fuller, ignorant (sheerly so; this is the glaring deficiency in my case) of " ID's argument structure", which is argument to the best explanation!
